            "content": "# Kconfiglib TODO\n\nTracks improvements, bugs, and upstream sync opportunities.\n\n## Upstream Reference\n\n- Zephyr Kconfiglib: https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/Kconfiglib\n- Original (archived): https://github.com/ulfalizer/Kconfiglib\n- Local reference: `externals/zephyr-Kconfiglib/`\n- C lxdialog reference: `mconf/` (original C-based mconf and lxdialog)\n  - Always check `mconf/lxdialog/*.c` for consistent behavior when modifying menuconfig dialogs\n  - Key files: `yesno.c` (yes/no dialog), `menubox.c` (menu), `util.c` (print_button, draw_box, themes)\n\n## Sync Status\n\n| File | This Project | Zephyr Upstream | Status |\n|------|--------------|-----------------|--------|\n| kconfiglib.py | 7619 lines | 7212 lines | Extended (+407) |\n| menuconfig.py | 3747 lines | 3278 lines | Extended (+469) |\n| guiconfig.py | 2899 lines | 2426 lines | Extended (+473) |\n\nLast reviewed: 2026-04-08\nUpstream reference: zephyrproject-rtos/Kconfiglib @ `a74dfcf`\n\n## High Priority\n\n### P1: Release pipeline is broken — fix before any release work\n- `release.yml:10` calls `test.yml` via `uses: ./.github/workflows/test.yml`, but\n  `test.yml:3` only declares `on: [push, pull_request]` and has no `workflow_call:` trigger\n- Result: tagging a release will fail immediately on the `test` job; the rest of P1 is moot until this is fixed\n- `package.yml` already has `workflow_call:` — mirror that in `test.yml`\n- Acceptance: a dry-run of `release.yml` (via `workflow_dispatch` on a throwaway tag, or `act`) reaches\n  the `package` and `release` jobs successfully\n\n### P2: UI range-helper regression tests (sysprog21#41 follow-up)\n- Issue #41 root cause: `sym.ranges` 4-tuples `(low, high, cond, loc)` unpacked as 3-tuples in\n  `menuconfig.py:3648`, `menuconfig.py:3676`, `guiconfig.py:1779`, `guiconfig.py:1818`\n- Code fix landed in `a5b6ecd`; the regression coverage has not\n- Action: add focused pytest coverage for `_range_info()` and `_check_valid()` in both\n  menuconfig.py and guiconfig.py against `tests/Krange`. Cover active-range and\n  all-ranges-disabled paths.\n- Existing range tests in `tests/test_symbols.py:246` cover the library, not the UI helpers — these\n  paths need their own targeted tests.\n- Note: broader API hardening (namedtuples for `ranges`/`defaults`/`selects`/`implies`) is tracked\n  separately as M13 below — it touches public data shape and is not required to prevent another #41.\n\n### P3: PyPI release with accumulated fixes\n- Depends on P1 (broken release wiring) and P2 (regression tests) landing first\n- `setup.py` version is `14.1.1a4`; PyPI lags 4+ months behind master\n- Issue #41 reporter hit a bug fixed long ago because of this lag\n- Action: cut a stable version, tag, publish a GitHub release to trigger the workflow\n- Acceptance: PyPI shows new stable; `pip install kconfiglib` ships ranges fix,\n  rawterm migration, transitional keyword, choice semantics, SYMBOL_WRITE, pytest migration\n- Pre-flight: bump version in `setup.py`, regenerate CHANGELOG headline,\n  smoke-test the built wheel from `.github/workflows/package.yml` artifact\n\n### P4: Synchronize Python support floor across all metadata\n- `setup.py` declares Python 3.6+ but `.github/workflows/test.yml:25-33` runs only 3.12, so the\n  3.6/3.8/3.10 claim is unverified\n- The floor is duplicated in `setup.py:58` (`python_requires`), `setup.py:71` (classifiers),\n  `pyproject.toml:2` (Ruff `target-version`), and module docstrings — fixing one without the others\n  leaves stale claims\n- Decision needed: keep claiming 3.6+ (and prove it in CI) or bump floor to 3.8\n- Action (single patch): make the decision, update all four locations in lockstep, expand the CI\n  matrix to {3.8, 3.10, 3.12, 3.13} on Linux at minimum (3.6/3.7 are EOL on GitHub-hosted runners)\n\n## Medium Priority\n\n### M1: Parser fuzzing for untrusted Kconfig input\n- `kconfiglib.py` parses recursive includes and complex regex; no fuzz coverage\n- ReDoS, infinite recursion, and stack overflow are all plausible attack surfaces\n  for tools that consume Kconfig from untrusted sources\n- Action: integrate `hypothesis` property-based testing for the lexer/parser, or\n  add an Atheris harness. Start with `Kconfig._parse_block()` and string-literal\n  handling.\n\n### M2: guiconfig jump-to filter for invalid items (zephyr#36)\n- Jump-to dialog shows all config items including invalid/invisible ones\n- Affected code: `guiconfig._update_jump_to_matches()` (around `guiconfig.py:2400`) iterates\n  `_sorted_sc_nodes()` without visibility check\n- Also applies to menuconfig jump-to dialog\n- Add toggle to filter out items that can't be set (similar to main \"Show All\" toggle)\n- Ready to implement — affected paths are isolated\n\n### M3: Test coverage reporting\n- CI runs pytest but emits no coverage data; #41 slipped through partly because\n  there was no visibility into which UI paths were tested\n- Note: focused regression tests (P2) are the primary fix; coverage reporting is the secondary\n  signal so the next gap is visible before a user reports it\n- Action: add `pytest-cov` to `.github/workflows/test.yml`, fail on coverage\n  regression below baseline. Upload to Codecov or store as workflow artifact.\n- Must run on the Linux/macOS jobs that exercise the full suite, not the\n  Windows headless-only subset\n\n### M4: Type hints for kconfiglib.py\n- ~7700-line single file with no type annotations\n- Modern editors/LSPs depend on type info for navigation and completion\n- Use native annotations (Python 3.6+ syntax)\n- Start with public API surface (`Kconfig`, `Symbol`, `Choice`, `MenuNode`), expand incrementally\n- Add a `py.typed` marker for PEP 561 compliance\n- Not a substitute for P2 regression tests — `mypy` only catches arity bugs once *both* sides are typed\n\n### M5: Recursive glob support for `source` (ulfalizer#102)\n- `source` glob does not support `**` recursive patterns\n- Current code: `iglob(join(self._srctree_prefix, pattern))` in `Kconfig._parse_block()`\n- C Kconfig does NOT support `**`. Bare `recursive=True` would create a silent\n  dialect fork — files we accept would fail under the kernel's host tools.\n- Required design: opt-in (e.g. `rsource_glob` keyword or env flag) and a\n  conformance test that the same file fails on `scripts/kconfig/conf`\n\n### M6: Supply-chain hygiene for the published package\n- No SBOM, no signed wheels, no dependency CVE monitoring\n- Risk: Kconfiglib runs `exec()` on Kconfig-supplied Python via `$(python,...)`\n  and `subprocess` for `cc-option` etc. — high blast radius if compromised\n- Cheap wins (do first): enable Dependabot for GitHub Actions pins; add `pip-audit` to CI\n- Speculative (separate item): Sigstore wheel signing, SBOM generation — defer until cheap wins land\n\n### M7: Screen reader accessibility (ulfalizer#126)\n- guiconfig resets cursor to top of screen instead of tracking current item\n- Makes the tool completely unusable with screen readers\n- Need proper focus management in Tkinter widgets\n- Consider `widget.focus_set()` and `widget.see()` calls after navigation\n\n### M8: Windows path separator normalization (zephyr#15)\n- `_enter_file()` produces mixed `\\` and `/` in filename paths on Windows\n- Stored in `self.filename`, propagated to warnings, loc tuples, and error messages\n- Fix: normalize to forward slashes in `_enter_file()`\n- Risk: can break downstream tools that do strict string comparison on paths\n\n### M9: menuconfig minimal-config save parity (ulfalizer#104)\n- guiconfig already exposes minimal-config save via `guiconfig.py:1853`; menuconfig does not\n- Real gap: add a minimal-save option to `menuconfig._save_dialog()` (`menuconfig.py:664`) so the\n  two UIs reach parity, and surface it via `--save-format=min|full` or env var\n- Drop the previous \"generic `--save-func`\" framing — `write_min_config()` already exists in the\n  library and the only missing piece is menuconfig UX\n\n### M10: Performance benchmark script (no CI gates yet)\n- No regression testing for parse performance on large Kconfig trees\n- Action: add `scripts/benchmark.py` timing `Kconfig(\"Kconfig\")` against the\n  pinned v6.18 Linux tree already checked out by `.github/workflows/test.yml`\n- Profile `menuconfig._shown_nodes()`, `guiconfig._update_tree()`, and rawterm\n  rendering separately so regressions can be attributed\n- Explicitly *not* doing CI failure gates yet — gates against GitHub-hosted runners + external\n  Linux tree are noisy until a stable baseline exists. Track gating as a separate L-item.\n\n### M11: Downstream consumer smoke test\n- This project is +407 lines ahead of upstream Zephyr; downstream consumers (Zephyr, ESP-IDF) can\n  break silently on API drift\n- Action: add a CI job that imports kconfiglib from this branch and runs a small representative\n  Kconfig from one of the downstream projects, asserting no exceptions and stable output\n- Cheap insurance against accidental breakage from the +400-line extensions\n\n### M12: pyproject.toml consolidation\n- Project has both `setup.py` and `pyproject.toml`; modern packaging (PEP 517/518) prefers\n  consolidating metadata into `pyproject.toml`\n- Action: move metadata into `pyproject.toml` with `setuptools.build_meta` backend\n- Keep `setup.py` only if it's still doing something `pyproject.toml` cannot express\n- Combines well with P4 (single source of truth for `python_requires`)\n\n### M13: Property tuple API hardening (deferred from P2)\n- Convert positional tuples to namedtuples (or accessor methods) for `ranges`, `defaults`,\n  `selects`, `implies`. Turns `ValueError: too many values to unpack` into `AttributeError` and\n  enables `r.low` / `r.cond` instead of positional indexing.\n- Keep tuple unpacking working for back-compat (namedtuples are tuples).\n- Touches public data shape — needs a deliberate API decision and downstream notification, not a\n  surprise refactor. Land regression tests (P2) first.\n- Subsumes the old M3 (orig_* tuple-length docs): once namedtuples land, attribute access removes\n  the asymmetry. If this item is dropped, fold the docs fix into a small standalone patch against\n  `kconfiglib.py:4919` and `kconfiglib.py:5989`.\n\n## Low Priority\n\n### L1: Snapshot/restore API for Kconfig state\n- Prerequisite for any undo/redo UX (zephyr#28). Real obstacle is not keystroke history but\n  snapshotting symbol state across cascading `select`/`imply`.\n- Scope this as a *library* feature first (snapshot/restore methods on `Kconfig`); UX comes later\n  or never.\n- Without this decomposition the original \"Ctrl+Z in menuconfig\" item rots in the backlog.\n\n### L2: Hide sub-options mode (zephyr#29)\n- Option to show only direct children of current menu\n- Complements existing \"Show All\" toggle\n\n### L3: oldaskconfig script (ulfalizer#133)\n- No equivalent of `--oldaskconfig` (line-oriented configuration)\n- Low demand but completeness gap vs. C tools\n\n### L4: Include guards in generated header (ulfalizer#95)\n- Add `#ifndef`/`#define` guards to generated config.h\n- Could be an optional flag to genconfig\n\n### L5: Benchmark CI regression gates\n- Follow-up to M10 — only meaningful once a baseline exists and noise floor is understood\n- Compare against stored baseline, fail on >10% regression (tunable)\n\n## Needs Reproduction / Policy Decision\n\nThese are not actionable until someone produces a failing fixture or makes a policy call. Do not\nschedule until prerequisites are met.\n\n### N1: String literal `%` cross-platform inconsistency (ulfalizer#114)\n- `%` in string literals handled differently across operating systems\n- Prerequisite: produce a minimal failing Kconfig that demonstrates the divergence (input symbol +\n  observed value on Linux vs Windows + expected) and cite the parsing path\n\n### N2: Escape characters in string values (ulfalizer#91)\n- `\\n`, `\\r`, `\\t` in string defaults resolve to literal characters (n, r, t); C Kconfig has\n  similar limitations\n- Prerequisite: decide policy first — match C semantics exactly or define our own escape table —\n  and document the chosen behavior with a failing test case before any code change. Must not break\n  Kconfig files using literal backslashes.\n\n## Removed\n\nThe following items were removed during the 2026-04-08 review. Reasons recorded so they don't get\nre-added without a fresh argument:\n\n- Old M3 (orig_* tuple-length docs): subsumed by M13. If M13 is dropped, fold the docs fix into a\n  one-line patch, not a tracked item.\n- Web-based configuration interface (ulfalizer#96): no product owner, large surface, no demand\n  signal. Resurrect only with a concrete user.\n- Merge symbol dependencies as AND (ulfalizer#142): would create a deliberate Kconfig dialect\n  fork — files we accept would fail under C Kconfig. Not worth the compatibility cost.\n- Local pre-commit hook (`.pre-commit-config.yaml`): CI already enforces ruff + black via\n  `.github/workflows/style.yml`; pre-commit is contributor convenience, not a project gap.\n\n## API Compatibility Notes\n\nWhen syncing with Zephyr, watch for:\n\n1. `Symbol.ranges` format: 4-tuples `(low, high, cond, loc)`. Use `orig_ranges` for 3-tuples.\n2. `Symbol.defaults` format: 3-tuples `(val, cond, loc)`. Use `orig_defaults` for 2-tuples.\n3. `sym.type` vs `sym.orig_type`: type may change due to TRISTATE->BOOL; orig_type never changes.\n\n## Sync Procedure\n\n```bash\ncd externals/zephyr-Kconfiglib\ngit fetch origin\ngit log HEAD..origin/main --oneline\n```\n\nTo evaluate a specific commit:\n```bash\ngit show <commit-hash>\ngit format-patch -1 <commit-hash> -o /tmp/patches/\ncd ../..\ngit apply --check /tmp/patches/*.patch\n```\n",
